@page "/wiki/agile-vs-waterfall"

@inject NavigationManager Navigation
@inject ISnackbar Snackbar

<MudPaper Class="px-6 py-4 ma-2" Elevation="4">
    <MudText Typo="Typo.h4">Comparing Software Development Methodologies</MudText>

    <MudText Typo="Typo.h5" Class="mt-4">Agile vs. Waterfall</MudText>
    <MudText Typo="Typo.body1" Class="mb-4">Agile and Waterfall are two prominent software development methodologies, each with distinct approaches and suitable use cases.</MudText>

    <MudExpansionPanels>
        <MudExpansionPanel Text="Waterfall" Expanded="false">
            <MudList T="string" Class="pl-4">
                <MudListItem>• Linear and Sequential: Waterfall is a linear approach where each phase must be completed before moving to the next.</MudListItem>
                <MudListItem>• Emphasis on Documentation: It provides thorough documentation at each stage, with clear milestones for progress tracking.</MudListItem>
                <MudListItem>
                    • Strengths:
                    <MudList T="string" Class="pl-4">
                        <MudListItem>- Clear structure and process flow</MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem>- Thorough documentation for each phase</MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem>- Easy progress tracking</MudListItem>
                    </MudList>
                </MudListItem>
                <MudListItem>
                    • Weaknesses:
                    <MudList T="string" Class="pl-4">
                        <MudListItem>- Inflexible to change once the process has started</MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem>- Late feedback, which can lead to higher risks in dynamic environments</MudListItem>
                    </MudList>
                </MudListItem>
                <MudListItem>• Ideal Use Cases: Projects with well-defined and stable requirements, minimal anticipated change, and a need for predictability. Examples: Government contracts, legacy system upgrades.</MudListItem>
            </MudList>
        </MudExpansionPanel>

        <MudExpansionPanel Text="Agile" Expanded="false">
            <MudList T="string" Class="pl-4">
                <MudListItem>• Iterative and Incremental: Agile focuses on rapid and flexible responses to change, developing software in iterative cycles.</MudListItem>
                <MudListItem>• Customer Collaboration: Agile emphasizes continuous customer involvement and delivering working software incrementally.</MudListItem>
                <MudListItem>
                    • Strengths:
                    <MudList T="string" Class="pl-4">
                        <MudListItem>- Adaptable to changing requirements</MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem>- Faster time to market and enhanced customer collaboration</MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem>- Focus on delivering value incrementally</MudListItem>
                    </MudList>
                </MudListItem>
                <MudListItem>
                    • Weaknesses:
                    <MudList T="string" Class="pl-4">
                        <MudListItem>- Can be challenging for teams unfamiliar with Agile principles</MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem>- Requires strong communication and collaboration</MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem>- Less suitable for projects with fixed requirements</MudListItem>
                    </MudList>
                </MudListItem>
                <MudListItem>• Ideal Use Cases: Projects with evolving requirements, rapid delivery needs, and high customer involvement. Examples: Mobile app development, software startups, projects in dynamic markets.</MudListItem>
            </MudList>
        </MudExpansionPanel>
    </MudExpansionPanels>
</MudPaper>